 on top of <br />1.3.88 will be the small fixes kind of thing rather than thing like the <br />NFS changes (first to use the page cache and then to do multithreading <br />requests).<br /><br />For example, I already have queued a patch-set that fixes some SCSI reset <br />handling problems (at least the linux-scsi channel people will recognize <br />the things that Leonard Zubkoff talked about some time ago). So 1.3.88 is <br />not going to be the same as 2.0 - you just shouldn't expect 2.0 to do <br />anything more.<br /><br />(Also, things like arch/m68k and arch/sparc are not bothered by the <br />codefreeze, because those architectures aren't "really supported" by the <br />default kernel sources anyway, and changing the architecture-specific <br />things there cannot break the x86 or alpha support).<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
